# Overtly Internal GTM Tool — Product Spec

## 1. Product Summary

Overtly needs an internal GTM operations tool to reduce manual sales work across LinkedIn and email outreach.

The first version focuses on LinkedIn.

The tool should not automate LinkedIn outreach. The user manually researches prospects, manually sends connection requests/messages, and manually follows up. The tool’s job is to log activity, organize follow-ups, capture replies/signals, and convert outbound work into measurable GTM intelligence.

The product should behave like an internal sales cockpit for Overtly’s outbound motion.

---

## 2. Core Principles

### 2.1 Manual outreach only

The tool must not:

* Auto-click LinkedIn buttons
* Auto-send connection requests
* Auto-send LinkedIn messages
* Bypass LinkedIn limits
* Run bulk scraping workflows
* Auto-open large numbers of profiles/search results

The tool may:

* Help log manually completed actions
* Show review popups
* Save user-confirmed prospect data
* Generate suggested follow-up text
* Let the user copy/paste manually
* Track outcomes and performance

### 2.2 User-confirmed data capture

Whenever the extension captures information from a LinkedIn profile, the user should review it before saving.

The system should prefer:

* User-confirmed profile details
* Manual correction
* Dropdowns/selectors for ambiguous fields
* Explicit Save actions

### 2.3 GTM intelligence over raw counting

The product should not just count activity. The main value is attribution.

The user should be able to answer:

* Which message version performs best?
* Which segment replies most?
* Which location performs best?
* Which sender account performs best?
* Which job titles respond?
* Which follow-up type gets replies?
* What objections/features/emails are coming from replies?

---

# Feature 1: LinkedIn Outbound Intelligence & Tracking

## 3. Feature Goal

Track manual LinkedIn outbound activity and convert it into organized GTM data.

The user should no longer need to maintain spreadsheets for connection requests, invite messages, sender account usage, message versions, locations, segments, and reply outcomes.

---

## 4. User Workflow

1. User manually researches a prospect on LinkedIn.
2. User manually sends a connection request/invite message.
3. Extension detects that a send action appears to have been completed.
4. Extension opens a review popup.
5. Popup contains prefilled details of the observed prospect.
6. User reviews and edits fields if needed.
7. User selects/validates segment and message version.
8. User clicks Save.
9. Record is stored in the database.
10. Dashboard updates activity, breakdowns, and performance metrics.

---

## 5. Review Popup

After a manual LinkedIn send, show a popup/modal/sidebar card.

### 5.1 Auto-filled fields

The popup should try to prefill:

* Prospect name
* Company
* Title / job
* Location
* LinkedIn profile URL
* Sent date
* Sent time
* Message text
* Message version / template
* LinkedIn account sent from

### 5.2 User-selected or user-confirmed fields

The user should be able to select or correct:

* Segment

  * Agency
  * In-house team
  * Founder
  * Consultant
  * Other
* ICP type
* Company type
* Region
* Message version
* Sender account
* Notes

### 5.3 Primary action

Button:

* Save

Optional secondary actions:

* Cancel
* Save as draft
* Edit fields
* Mark as duplicate / already logged

---

## 6. Data Stored

Each logged outbound action should create a record.

### 6.1 LinkedIn outreach event fields

* ID
* Created at
* Updated at
* Sent at
* Channel: LinkedIn
* Sender account
* Prospect name
* LinkedIn profile URL
* Company
* Title / job
* Location
* Segment
* ICP type
* Company type
* Region
* Message text
* Message version / template ID
* Status
* Notes

### 6.2 Status lifecycle

Supported statuses:

* Sent
* Accepted
* Replied
* Positive reply
* Follow-up needed
* Meeting booked
* Not interested
* Closed lost
* Archived

---

## 7. LinkedIn Dashboard

The dashboard should show both activity and GTM performance.

### 7.1 Activity metrics

* Sent today
* Sent this week
* Sent this month
* Sent by sender account
* Sent by message version
* Sent by location
* Sent by region
* Sent by segment
* Sent by title / job type

### 7.2 Funnel metrics

Track:

* Sent
* Accepted
* Replied
* Positive replies
* Meetings booked
* Not interested

### 7.3 Performance metrics

Show:

* Acceptance rate by message version
* Reply rate by message version
* Positive reply rate by message version
* Meeting rate by message version
* Performance by sender account
* Performance by segment
* Performance by geography
* Performance by title/job

### 7.4 Dashboard views

Useful views:

* Weekly summary
* Account-wise activity
* Message version performance
* Segment performance
* Location/geography breakdown
* Prospect list
* Replies list
* Follow-up queue

---

# Feature 2: LinkedIn Follow-Up Workbench + Reply Signal Capture

## 8. Feature Goal

Help the user follow up with the right people without manually scrolling back through LinkedIn messages.

The system should use the logged outreach database to show who needs follow-up, generate a personalized suggested message based on previous context, and allow the user to copy/paste/send manually.

The system should also capture important reply signals such as feature requests, objections, email addresses, and next actions.

---

## 9. Problem 1: Follow-up friction

Current problems:

* User hates scrolling many days back to find people to follow up with.
* User needs to send unique follow-ups based on previous messages.
* It is hard to remember who was contacted, when, and with what message.
* It is hard to know whether someone needs follow-up 1, follow-up 2, or another next action.

---

## 10. Follow-Up Queue

The dashboard should show a queue of prospects who need action.

Example queue item:

* Prospect name
* Company
* Title
* LinkedIn URL
* Sender account
* Original message
* Original message version
* Date first sent
* Days since sent
* Last interaction date
* Current status
* Follow-up stage
* Suggested next action

### 10.1 Follow-up stages

Supported stages:

* No follow-up yet
* Follow-up 1 due
* Follow-up 1 sent
* Follow-up 2 due
* Follow-up 2 sent
* Follow-up 3 due
* Follow-up 3 sent
* Replied
* Paused
* Archived

### 10.2 Follow-up states

Supported states:

* Due
* Not due yet
* Sent
* Read, not responded
* Replied
* Skipped
* Snoozed
* Do not follow up

---

## 11. Follow-Up Workflow

1. User opens Follow-Up Workbench.
2. System shows prospects due for follow-up.
3. User clicks a prospect.
4. System shows previous outreach context.
5. System generates a suggested follow-up message.
6. User clicks Open LinkedIn.
7. User manually pastes/sends the message on LinkedIn.
8. User returns to tool/extension and marks follow-up as sent.
9. System records follow-up stage, message version, sent date/time, and status.

The system must not auto-send LinkedIn messages.

---

## 12. Personalized Follow-Up Message Generation

The follow-up generator should use:

* Prospect name
* Company
* Title/job
* Segment
* Original message
* Previous message version
* Days since last message
* Reply status
* Accepted/not accepted status
* Any known notes
* Overtly positioning
* Follow-up stage

The generated message should be short, natural, and copy-paste friendly.

The user should be able to:

* Copy message
* Regenerate
* Edit manually
* Select tone
* Save message version
* Mark as sent

---

## 13. Problem 2: Reply and Signal Capture

Current problems:

* Some prospects accept and reply.
* Some ask questions like “Do you have XYZ feature?”
* Some share email addresses like “mail me at [abc@company.com](mailto:abc@company.com).”
* Some give objections or feedback.
* These signals get lost.
* User forgets to follow up properly.
* There is no dashboard for why people responded or which follow-up worked.

---

## 14. Reply Capture Workflow

When a prospect replies, the user should be able to log it.

Options:

* Paste reply manually into the extension/dashboard.
* Select existing prospect.
* Save reply.
* System classifies/extracts useful information.

### 14.1 Reply fields

Store:

* Reply ID
* Outreach event ID
* Prospect ID
* Reply date/time
* Reply text
* Reply type
* Sentiment
* Interest level
* Feature mentioned
* Objection mentioned
* Email address mentioned
* Feedback
* Next action
* Follow-up stage at time of reply

### 14.2 Reply types

Supported reply types:

* Interested
* Feature question
* Pricing question
* Email handoff
* Referral
* Objection
* Not now
* Not interested
* Booked meeting
* Other

### 14.3 Extracted signals

The system should extract:

* Requested feature
* Feedback
* Objection
* Email address to contact
* Person to contact
* Timing cue
* Buying intent
* Next action

Examples:

Reply: “Do you have media monitoring?”
Extract:

* Reply type: Feature question
* Feature requested: Media monitoring
* Next action: Answer feature question

Reply: “Mail me at [abc@company.com](mailto:abc@company.com)”
Extract:

* Reply type: Email handoff
* Email: [abc@company.com](mailto:abc@company.com)
* Next action: Send email

Reply: “Not now, maybe next quarter”
Extract:

* Reply type: Not now
* Timing cue: Next quarter
* Next action: Snooze follow-up

---

## 15. Follow-Up Analytics Dashboard

The follow-up dashboard should show:

* Follow-up 1 sent this week
* Follow-up 2 sent this week
* Follow-up 3 sent this week
* Replies received after follow-up
* Positive replies after follow-up
* Read but not responded
* Follow-ups due today
* Follow-ups overdue
* Best-performing follow-up version
* Best-performing follow-up stage
* Common objections
* Common requested features
* Emails collected
* Follow-up response rate by segment
* Follow-up response rate by title
* Follow-up response rate by geography
* Follow-up response rate by sender account

Example dashboard insights:

* “Follow-up 1 was sent to 10 people this week.”
* “4 people replied after follow-up 1.”
* “Most replies came from agency founders.”
* “Follow-up V2 performed better than Follow-up V1.”
* “Most common feature question: media monitoring.”
* “3 prospects shared email addresses for follow-up.”

